def rmse(y_true, y_pred):
    return mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred, squared=False)
def rmse_score():
    return make_scorer(rmse, greater_is_better=False)

from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ReduceLROnPlateau

filepath="best_model_2.h5"
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(filepath=filepath, monitor='val_root_mean_squared_error', save_best_only=True, mode='auto')

def scheduler(epoch, lr):
    if epoch < 10:
        return lr
    else:
        return lr * tf.math.exp(-0.1)

reduce_lr = tf.keras.callbacks.LearningRateScheduler(scheduler)

model = Model(inputs = [inputc1, inputc2, inputc3, inputc4, inputc5, inputc6, inputc7, inputc8, inputc9, inputc10, inputc11, inputc12, inputc13, inputc14], outputs = output)
model.compile(loss='mse', 
   optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.01,clipnorm=1.0,clipvalue=0.05), 
   metrics=[tf.keras.metrics.RootMeanSquaredError()])

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
 
fig = plt.subplots(figsize =(12, 6)) 
# creating an array of data for x-axis
x = np.array([i for i in range(len(history.history['loss']))])
 
# data for y-axis
loss = history.history['loss']
val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
 
# data for y-axis for another plot
root_mean_squared_error = history.history['root_mean_squared_error']
val_root_mean_squared_error = history.history['val_root_mean_squared_error']

# using subplot function and creating plot one
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)  # row 1, column 2, count 1
plt.plot(x, loss, 'r')
plt.plot(x, val_loss, 'g')
plt.title('LOSS VS EPOCH')
plt.xlabel('EPOCHS')
plt.ylabel('LOSS')
plt.legend(["Training", "Testing"])
# using subplot function and creating plot two
# row 1, column 2, count 2
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
 
# g is for green color
plt.plot(x, root_mean_squared_error, 'r')
plt.plot(x, val_root_mean_squared_error, 'g')
plt.title('RMSE VS EPOCH')
plt.xlabel('EPOCHS')
plt.ylabel('RMSE')

# space between the plots
# plt.tight_layout(4)
# using padding
plt.tight_layout(pad=5.0)
plt.legend(["Training", "Testing"])#, frameon=legend_drawn_flag)
# show plot
plt.show()

filepath="best_model_5.h5"
checkpoint = tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath=filepath, monitor='val_root_mean_squared_error', save_best_only=True, mode='auto')

def scheduler(epoch, lr):
    if epoch < 10:
        return lr
    else:
        return lr * tf.math.exp(-0.1)

reduce_lr = tf.keras.callbacks.LearningRateScheduler(scheduler)

model = Model(inputs = [input1, input2, input3, input4, inputc1, inputc2, inputc3, inputc4, inputc5, inputc6, inputc7, inputc8, inputc9, inputc10, inputc11, inputc12, inputc13, inputc14], outputs = output)
model.compile(loss='mse', 
   optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.01,clipnorm=1.0,clipvalue=0.05), 
   metrics=[tf.keras.metrics.RootMeanSquaredError()])

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
 
fig = plt.subplots(figsize =(12, 6)) 
# creating an array of data for x-axis
x = np.array([i for i in range(len(history.history['loss']))])
 
# data for y-axis
loss = history.history['loss']
val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
 
# data for y-axis for another plot
root_mean_squared_error = history.history['root_mean_squared_error']
val_root_mean_squared_error = history.history['val_root_mean_squared_error']

# using subplot function and creating plot one
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)  # row 1, column 2, count 1
plt.plot(x, loss, 'r')
plt.plot(x, val_loss, 'g')
plt.title('LOSS VS EPOCH')
plt.xlabel('EPOCHS')
plt.ylabel('LOSS')
plt.legend(["Training", "Testing"])
# using subplot function and creating plot two
# row 1, column 2, count 2
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
 
# g is for green color
plt.plot(x, root_mean_squared_error, 'r')
plt.plot(x, val_root_mean_squared_error, 'g')
plt.title('RMSE VS EPOCH')
plt.xlabel('EPOCHS')
plt.ylabel('RMSE')

# space between the plots
# plt.tight_layout(4)
# using padding
plt.tight_layout(pad=5.0)
plt.legend(["Training", "Testing"])#, frameon=legend_drawn_flag)
# show plot
plt.show()
